 book illustrates not just the Victorian city’s vibrant public life but also the intense social tensions and cultural differences within the city. Drawing from journalists’ accounts in newspapers, Expressive Acts illuminates what drove Torontonians to claim public space, where their passions lay, and how they gave expression to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDemonstrationszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aDemonstrationszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  a1885.  aCanadian history.  aNorth-West Resistance.  aOrange-Green conflict.  aPrince of Wales.  aToronto.  acelebrations.  acrowds.  ademonstrations.  aelection campaigns.  ahistory.  ajournalism.  anewspapers.  astrikes.  aurban studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754579640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487545796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487545796/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles